   <mads:note type="source">Oxford class. dict., 1st ed.: p. 355 (Fabius Pictor Quintus; Roman
      senator and historian; wrote a history of Rome in Greek. The Latin annuals,if not a later
      adaptation, may belong to Ser. Fabius, the work De iure pontificio to Fabius Servilianus)</mads:note>
   <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "F. Pictor, Q. First Roman historian, works written in Greek, 3rd/2nd cent. BC...
      The work that probably comprises several books (Pol. 3,9,3) written in Greek (Dion. Hal. Ant. Rom. 1,6,2) and is 
      quoted by Latin authors (fr. 3; 24; 27 P.) as Annales ( Annalists) has been lost apart from a few testimonia
      that speak of Italian (and Sicilian?: fr. 2; 3A P.) ancient history with Hercules, Lanuvinus and Aeneas 
      and ‘much later’ (i.e. according to the kings' list of Alba in accordance with the Eratosthenian chronology) 
      of Romulus, Remus and the founding of Rome [4] and goes up to 217 (fr. 26 P.)/216 BC (App. Hann. 116)...."
      Scholz, Udo W. (Würzburg) “Fabius”, in: Brill’s New Pauly, Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and , Helmuth Schneider,
      English Edition by: Christine F. Salazar, Classical Tradition volumes edited by: Manfred Landfester, English Edition by: Francis G. Gentry. 
      Consulted online on 16 September 2019 http://dx.doi.org/10.1163/1574-9347_bnp_e408370
   </mads:note>
